snippet.textDisplay: I got into the ecosystem in duress.  I'm a PC guy and that translated into a distaste for apple in general.  I needed/wanted the app market and planned to get 1 iphone - EVER - assuming android would be as competative as the apple marketplace by the next iteration.  I bought a Pixel and Pixelbuds as my first iphone began to age out.  Pixel 3a was fantastic but the Pixelbuds were SO BAD i returned them, returned the phone, and bought a $150 iphone replacement.  Then spent $250 on the pro pods.  I'm eagerly awaiting an exit ramp from this ecosystem, but am staggered by how effective the improved experience is.  I am looking at used ::shudders:: macbooks ::gags:: to enable slightly more lazy interfacing.   These mofos earned their trillion IMO.

snippet.textDisplay:
Yes. It's almost as if iPhone users are total sheep. The iPhone costs went down, the price went up, and the solution cost a significant amount of cash.

Apple shouldn't be applauded, and the entire industry deserves to literally have a 60 pound sack of diarrhea dropped on their collective desks. Apple showed the proof of concept. I refused to upgrade my LG V30 to another LG, because all my local store had were jackless.

The "best possible wireless earbuds" technology is, again, a crock of crap. Because that technology is obscenely expensive. You can spend $30 on wired earbuds and they'll last a couple years. But $30 wireless earbuds?

Hahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahaha... hahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahahaha

No. They're either non-existent of worse than crap. Crap can fertilize something. Apple's courageously stupid decision signalled that if you want decent audio in the future, you need to pay $100 at the low end for decent quality.

So "copying Apple" really means "if Apple sheep [yes. I've had multiple iPhones. I won't buy another. You're all sheep.] are willing to spend $8 billion on earbuds, we should be scumbags too. We have to be competitive."

So. Yes. Apple are the dregs of the mobile industry. It's a race to the bottom of the barrel, and Apple just found a new bottom!
